Author: janos.csizmazia@ligo.org

Report ID: 79516

Today's activities:

- In order to advance further safely, the instrument air system needed to be fixed, at least temporarily, but reliably. Currently the Kobelco compressor is being used as an instrument air compressor, for details, see aLog: https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=79512

- The HAM6 turbo was started up with its designated backing cart. This cart needs instrument air, as one if its safety valves is pneumatic. This turbo was running for 2-3 hours before it was valved in, to eliminate any potential risks with the inst. air
- The HAM6 turbo was valved in at ~12:50. The pressure immediately went down in HAM6 by 2E-6 Torr, and in the corner in general by 5E-7 Torr

- The HAM5/HAM6 annulus system pumpdown continued. The Annulus Ion Pumps have been also switched on, and after some struggle they came alive. The pumping carts are still there though, they are at <1E-5 Torr
- As HAM7 caught up with the relay tube, the pumping of the relay tube was stopped, and it was valved together with HAM7 (RV-2 open)
- The rebuilt HAM6 RGA is being pumped, before it will be baked out, starting with next Monday. A pumping cart has been brought from the FCES for this purpose

Author: jeffrey.kissel@ligo.org

Report ID: 79513

J. Kissel

Took the opportunity to grab post-OFI-repair vent, in-vac transfer functions of the following HAM5 and HAM6 SUS. Of course, we're not at full observing-level vacuum, but most of the molecules are out of the chamber that would contribute to buoyancy, so the SUS are at the position they will be in observing-level vacuum.
Executive summary: I'm happy with all SUS that I measured -- including the two that were ""interesting"" and or touched during this vent -- SRM and OFI.
For the story about SRM, see LHO:79433.
And of course, the OFI had had optics replaced.

Several other SUS in HAM5 / 6 were not touched during the vent (aside from a few alignment sliders), so we didn't expect any degradation in performance and don't see any. These SUS are ready to resume observing gravitational waves!
Processed results will be posted as comments below.
Some relevant details of the status of the suspensions and their surroundings during the measurements.

Author: tyler.guidry@ligo.org

Report ID: 79512

Presently the instrument air supply to the Corner Station is supplied via a piston style compressor at the chiller yard where it feeds underground to the Mechanical Room. Beginning on Sunday, the compressor failed to maintain the pressure required at the GV's. Since then, Facilities has been preparing to install a new, scroll style compressor and drying tower to replace the old and partially decommissioned system.

Given that taking the old compressor completely out of service for the swap will completely remove the supply of air to the instrument air system, and that in parallel we have the Kobelco running, I have tapped into the outlet of the Kobelco (post-dryer). In the past this has fed the manifold for the TMDS system but is currently not in use.

Using a basic off the shelf air regulator behind a ball valve, I have set the feed pressure at ~70psi. An analog gauge on the instrument air piping reinforced this. As this is very much a temporary system, between this new addition and the instrument airline is a basic compressor hose connected via quick disconnect fittings.

In conjunction with re-routing the supply air, I have valved out the feed line from the old compressor inside the Mechanical Room. This does two things; First, it will prevent us from unnecessarily charging the line from the mechanical room back to the chiller yard. And two, will allow us to monitor the behavior of the old compressor over the weekend whilst demand is lifted from it. With demand lifted and the blow-down disabled, should we see any activity from the compressor, we know there is most likely a leak between the two points and will require further investigation.
Attached photos of the connections between Kobelco>IA and compressor runtime at time of blowdown disable.
R. McCarthy G. Moreno J. Csizmazia T. GuidryVE

Author: genevieve.connolly@ligo.org

Report ID: 79507

On Monday Aug 5 around 21:00 UTC, Sam and I went looking for several accelerometers that LigoCAM reported were disconnected: H1:PEM-CS_ACC_HAM5_SRM_X_DQ, H1:PEM-CS_ACC_HAM5_SRM_Y_DQ, H1:PEM-CS_ACC_HAM6_OMC_X_DQ, and H1:PEM-CS_ACC_LVEAFLOOR_BS_Y_DQ. We found that the switch for H1:PEM-CS_ACC_LVEAFLOOR_BS_Y_DQ was turned off in the electronics bay so we turned it back on and it is now connected. Yesterday Wednesday Aug 7 between 19:40-20:09 UTC, I went back with Janos' help to take care of the other three accelerometers. The cords at the accelerometers had been disconnected for opening the HAM chambers, so we plugged them back in. All of these accelerometers are now connected, with confirmation from LigoCAM."

Author: janos.csizmazia@ligo.org

Report ID: 79504

Today's activities:
- The HAM5/HAM6 annulus system pumpdown continues. The Turbo backing line is already at around ~1E-5 Torr

- The pumpdown of the corner has continued. The pressure as of this writing is 9E-1 Torr, which indicates that the Turbos can be switched on tomorrow. A pressure update will be in the comments, when the roughing pumps will be stopped for today
- The pumpdown of HAM7 and the relay tube continues. HAM7 will catch up with the relay tube tomorrow, and so those 2 volumes will be valved together
- The mobile cleanroom in the FCT was pushed above C-4 position, as a gauge will be added there shortly - see pic.

- The instrument air system will be bypassed with the Kobelco compressor, as the inst. air compressor keeps failing (for more detail see aLog: https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=79503)

36,LHO VE - 8-6 vent vacuum diary,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=79485,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Tue, 06 Aug 2024 19:30:14 -0700",[],"{'term': 'LHO VE', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: janos.csizmazia@ligo.org

Report ID: 79485

Today's activities:
- The relay tube was installed, and was leak checked: no leaks bigger than 1E-10 Torr have been detected
- The HAM5/HAM6 annulus system is being pumped down. The Turbo backing line is already at around ~4E-5 Torr

- The Mobile pumping station with 2 pcs. of ISP1000 pumping carts and with the mobile transformer has been installed next to the OMC Turbo station (see picture, and see the PID according to LIGO-E2300443-v1 Main volume Double Mobile Scroll Turbo Startup Procedure, Appendix II.)
- The checklist for pumpdown has been done according to LIGO-E2300169-v2
- The dew point at the OMC venting port in the chamber was measured -38.9 deg C, which is surprisingly good (details: https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=79483)

- The pumpdown of the corner has started. With the Double ISP-1000 carts it is pretty quick: the pumpdown started at 16:15, and at 19:07 the pressure is already 167 Torr, which means 1900 l/min (at the Turbo station, as the pressure is already <100, it is well over 2000 l/min, as it should be)

- The pumpdown of HAM7 has also started, it is pretty fast, as it was anticipated, since no doors were opened there. It is already at 1.2E-5 Torr. See details here: https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=79482

As you can see in both pictures, the HAM5-HAM6-HAM7 area is very busy with vacuum equipment, so please only go there if it is absolutely necessary, and if you do, be very careful. Especially the Pfeiffer pumping carts can tip over easily (remember last pumpdown), and in general, Turbo pumps don't like movement - they can easily trip off. Now there are 2 Pfeiffer pumping carts, 3 more small Pfeiffer turbos, a leak checker, a supersucker cart, the new double ISP-1000 mobile pumping station, and the HAM7 turbo up and running.
There were a couple of other issues, too:
- The PT-154 (MKS) gauge, between HAM7 and BSC3 on the FCT, falsely shows 1E-3 Torr. It needs replacement, which will be done after O4

- The instrument air compressor failed to switch on one more time at around 16:45. The aLog about the last failure is here: https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=79443. It was restarted with some struggle, but it seems that the only real solution is to replace it. A Nitrogen and a compressed air bottle was staged in the mechanical room, just in case

45,H1 CDS - Reducing end station Dolphin card temps by redirecting airflow,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=79477,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Tue, 06 Aug 2024 16:10:59 -0700","[

EJ, Marc, Jonathan, Erik, Dave:

,

EJ noted that the Dolphin PCIe cards located at the endstations and read out by h1cdsrfm in the corner are running much warmer than the rest of the Dolphin cards.

,

h1cdsrfm has 3 Dophin IX cards on its PCI bus, one is plugged into its local PCIe bank, the other two are in Adnaco expansion chassis which are located at the end stations, and are accessed by a 4km single mode fiber link connected to local adnaco adapter cards.

,

The local Dolhin card, cooled by h1cdsrfm's fans, runs at 62C. The EY card runs at 74C and the EX card runs at 90C. The end station temps are significantly higher than the manufacturer's recommendation.

,

The Adnaco expansion chassis were inspected at both end stations:

,

   both chassis side mounted, resting on a shelf

,

  both chassis have their cover installed

,

  both chassis fan is operational

,

The only difference between the two end stations is the PCIe slot the Dolphin card is installed in. At EY (74C) it is in the slot closest to the fan (closest to center of chassis), at EX (90C) it is the slot furthest from the fan (closest to the edge of chassis).

,

The chassis has one airflow outlet, the fan itself blowing outwards at the rear. There are several airflow inlets: circular hole pattern on top lid, center of the chassis; rectangular hole pattern on top lid, directly above the four PCIe slots; series of slots on left side, from front of chassis to half way back; ditto on right side.

,

At 14:06 at EY we put a plate on the top lid which blocks the circular hole pattern. Now air comes in from the holes directly above the PCIe slots, and the left and right slot array. This cooled the Dolphin card down from 74C to 65C in 30mins.

,

At 15:00 at EX we put a plate on the circular pattern, and blocked the right side slot array with tape. Now input air is directly above the PCI connectors and on the left side array only (the one closest to the cards)

,

Attached trend shows EX and EY temps over this period, started with 90C,74C and now at a steady 76C,66C

]","{'term': 'H1 CDS', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

EJ, Marc, Jonathan, Erik, Dave:
EJ noted that the Dolphin PCIe cards located at the endstations and read out by h1cdsrfm in the corner are running much warmer than the rest of the Dolphin cards.

h1cdsrfm has 3 Dophin IX cards on its PCI bus, one is plugged into its local PCIe bank, the other two are in Adnaco expansion chassis which are located at the end stations, and are accessed by a 4km single mode fiber link connected to local adnaco adapter cards.

The local Dolhin card, cooled by h1cdsrfm's fans, runs at 62C. The EY card runs at 74C and the EX card runs at 90C. The end station temps are significantly higher than the manufacturer's recommendation.
The Adnaco expansion chassis were inspected at both end stations:
both chassis side mounted, resting on a shelf
both chassis have their cover installed

The only difference between the two end stations is the PCIe slot the Dolphin card is installed in. At EY (74C) it is in the slot closest to the fan (closest to center of chassis), at EX (90C) it is the slot furthest from the fan (closest to the edge of chassis).

The chassis has one airflow outlet, the fan itself blowing outwards at the rear. There are several airflow inlets: circular hole pattern on top lid, center of the chassis; rectangular hole pattern on top lid, directly above the four PCIe slots; series of slots on left side, from front of chassis to half way back; ditto on right side.

At 14:06 at EY we put a plate on the top lid which blocks the circular hole pattern. Now air comes in from the holes directly above the PCIe slots, and the left and right slot array. This cooled the Dolphin card down from 74C to 65C in 30mins.

At 15:00 at EX we put a plate on the circular pattern, and blocked the right side slot array with tape. Now input air is directly above the PCI connectors and on the left side array only (the one closest to the cards)
Attached trend shows EX and EY temps over this period, started with 90C,74C and now at a steady 76C,66C

58,L1 SQZ - Comment to Brief summary of 71W power-up commissioning,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=72594,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Sun, 11 Aug 2024 14:55:51 -0500","[

Some notes on the squeezer and TCS changes: 

,

With the 71W configuration, with TCS changes, I've been making adjustments to bring the squeezing level to ~ -5.3 dB levels using the squeezer phase. This change mostly accounts for the path length change due to the thermo-refractive changes experienced by the test masses, i.e. wavefront distortion within the substrates. To correct for the quadratic mode-mismatch between the IFO beam and the squeezed beam, due to the thermo-elastic surface deformation effect, we will need to sweep the ZM4 and ZM5 PSAMS, i.e. the defocus on the squeezed beam.

As important as the wavefront curvature, misalignment of a beam also imprints an effective tilt on the wavefront, compromising the mode-matching, i.e. the electric field overlap. So, to recover our optimal squeezing level of ~ -5.8 dB with the new TCS settings, we will need to perform fine alignment scans as well as the PSAM scans.

,

For context: Fast alignment with the SQZ guardian was attempted and yielded no improvement for the 71 W case. We have seen the need for the fine alignment and PSAM scans in keeping the squeezing level up for various thermal states: the recovery of -5.7 dB squeezing with 63.5 W alogs 72160 72287, the drop to 56 W alog 72249, partial recovery work after going back up to 63.5 W alog 72441.

,

Shot noise comparison with comparable squeezing levels: 

,

Attached is a DARM plot showing representative strains for the three different power levels, with comparable squeezing level at ~ -5.4 dB. The black trace is taken with 71 W, the purple trace is with 63.5 W, and the green trace is with 56.7 W input power. The high frequency noise around 4-7 kHz is also comparable for the 63.5 W and 71 W cases. Low frequency noise looks about the same for all three power levels in this plot, with the improvement in shot noise with increasing power visible >300 Hz.

These strains were chosen from times where we are not hindered by the low frequnecy nonstationary noise that shows up sporadically. The measurements are taken over a 10 minute period in each case. The dtt location: /data/begum.kabagoz/TCS_and_SQZ/gds_calib_strain_comparison.xml

,

71 W:      2024/08/10  02:46:38 -  02:56:38  UTC

56.7 W:   2024/07/23  10:20:04 -  10:30:04  UTC

]","{'term': 'L1 SQZ', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Some notes on the squeezer and TCS changes:

With the 71W configuration, with TCS changes, I've been making adjustments to bring the squeezing level to ~ -5.3 dB levels using the squeezer phase. This change mostly accounts for the path length change due to the thermo-refractive changes experienced by the test masses, i.e. wavefront distortion within the substrates. To correct for the quadratic mode-mismatch between the IFO beam and the squeezed beam, due to the thermo-elastic surface deformation effect, we will need to sweep the ZM4 and ZM5 PSAMS, i.e. the defocus on the squeezed beam.

As important as the wavefront curvature, misalignment of a beam also imprints an effective tilt on the wavefront, compromising the mode-matching, i.e. the electric field overlap. So, to recover our optimal squeezing level of ~ -5.8 dB with the new TCS settings, we will need to perform fine alignment scans as well as the PSAM scans.

For context: Fast alignment with the SQZ guardian was attempted and yielded no improvement for the 71 W case. We have seen the need for the fine alignment and PSAM scans in keeping the squeezing level up for various thermal states: the recovery of -5.7 dB squeezing with 63.5 W alogs 72160 72287, the drop to 56 W alog 72249, partial recovery work after going back up to 63.5 W alog 72441.
Shot noise comparison with comparable squeezing levels:

Attached is a DARM plot showing representative strains for the three different power levels, with comparable squeezing level at ~ -5.4 dB. The black trace is taken with 71 W, the purple trace is with 63.5 W, and the green trace is with 56.7 W input power. The high frequency noise around 4-7 kHz is also comparable for the 63.5 W and 71 W cases. Low frequency noise looks about the same for all three power levels in this plot, with the improvement in shot noise with increasing power visible >300 Hz.

These strains were chosen from times where we are not hindered by the low frequnecy nonstationary noise that shows up sporadically. The measurements are taken over a 10 minute period in each case. The dtt location: /data/begum.kabagoz/TCS_and_SQZ/gds_calib_strain_comparison.xml

79,L1 ISC - Power Up 2.7 Hz issues continue,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=72574,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Fri, 09 Aug 2024 17:48:04 -0500","[

JoeB, Anamaria

,

Seems our fix from yesterday didn't fix everything. A few notes, since we still don't understand the mechanism:
- we measured ASC MICH P and Y, they are fine;
- we measured the OMC OLG, it's at 10 Hz instead of 20 Hz but still enough phase margin (we'll consult Adam Monday if to raise the gain for good);
- we tried slightly increasing the SRC2 gains, from 1 to 1.2, that didn't help;
- we decreased the CHARD P gain from 0.3 to 0.2 during the power up, and put it back later, but unclear if this helped (there's no instability in CHARD at 2.7 but there may be one around 2 Hz);
- several ASC signals see it, but not large enough to explain the size of it in DARM;

- OMC yaw signals see it at perhaps worrisome level, and larger there first than in DARM.

,

The SRC2 loop only gets turned on every other power step, strangely, and doesn't fully converge by the time it's turned off to do another step. The two times we lost lock in the final power up stage due to 2.7 Hz instability today, it was some 1min - 30 sec or so after it had been re-engaged.

85,L1 ISC - Brief summary of 71W power-up commissioning,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=72568,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Fri, 09 Aug 2024 12:43:33 -0500","[

Valera, Adam, Begum, Karla, Vlad, JoeB, Anamaria

,

For the past some 10 days we've been running at ~71W input power, above the nominal ~64W. I will try to summarize some of our activities and findings so far.

,

In the first 3 plots I show the same top two panels and time span, and then different signals related to different observations (so they're more visible than if I were to plot 10 panels). The top plot is the input power over the past 20 days. We had to operate at even lower power (56W) for a bit because the CO2 alignment had been lost, so it's interesting to compare the 3 input power behaviors. The second plot is kappa_c, the indicator of optical gain; it should not change with power the way it is calculated. We always lose a bit of optical gain as we go up in power, but it's superficially still worth it if we lose less than we gain in shot noise level. 

,

In the first plot attached, the third signal is the POP power, calibrated in W in the PRC. Based on Valera's estimate of arm power, we think this corresponds to ~280kW/307kW/335kW circulating in the arm for the 3 power settings. The next signal is the 9 mHz buildup in the PRC, scaled by input power. It seems to go down no matter what. For reference, the current ~1700 value corresponds to a buildup of 70, while the perfect mode matching estimate is ~120. The 45 MHz buildup is much smaller by design, ~13 in a perfect world, and it does something similar to the 9MHz so I don't show it here.

,

This 9 MHz buildup drop has us concerned about the stability of various loops, since it's the identical behavior that LHO saw during their highest power operations. We measured the PRCL loop as a good indicator of this, but it seems to so far not lose too much gain. Adam also measured the CARM loop yesterday, and it seemed a bit not ideal, he will post details separately, but more measurements are necessary and we will do them in the next commissioning period. 

,

In the second plot attached, I show also range (after calibration) with optical gain and squeezer performance, since both affect range significantly. With every power adjustment and large TCS changes, the squeezer has to be readjusted, which Begum has been doing this entire period. During all these changes, albeit small in the grand scheme of things, the range seems slightly  lower for the higher power, but that's to be expected for the optimization period. We've definitely found a better thermal state in the past few days and we hope to get some more data to have a more fair comparison with the nominal 64W operation.

,

In the third plot attached, I show some of the TCS setting changes. At 56W we can afford to run without CO2, which is a good state to have automated in case of hardware issues. We then tried two different settings at 71W, ~2.0W and ~2.4W. We were hoping we can trade CO2 for ITM ring heater to increase the sideband buildup without losing optical gain (because they have different lensing versus curvature effect). So far we can't say we found this to be true or quantified it, but we will continue. With the higher CO2 setting we were indeed able to reduce the ITM RH power below the 64W settings to increase the optical gain. We have not tested much ETM ring heater effects yet, still to check.
We are also trying to decipher if the Hartmann signals and the SIM signals could be useful for tuning, we will separately make a report on that.

Vlad will post an optical mode shift report in various configurations, to see if we can use it for carrier mode matching improvement.

,

Thermal transient: it does seem to be much longer as we increase the nominal low noise CO2 values. We are trying to understand it to see if we can speed it up. Right now we apply about half of it right after DC readout, and the rest after we've powered up, but there's no matching done with the central transient. This alone could be an argument for running at lower power, since we lose range in the first few hours of the lock, especially because of the squeezer transient that has elongated as well.

The differential element also has a long trasient (not shown), long locks start with higher frequency coupling, which then goes down over a few hours and settles at a reasonable value. This can be seen directly in DARM at ~5-6kHz where the frequency noise is close: when that region has a bump, we have more coupling/contrast defect/differential lensing.

,

Noise:  We don't have a deep assessment yet of the noise comparison, there may be a bit of low frequency noise at the higher power, but that's confounded with squeezer operation. We will post a noise curve later. Aside from a ~20 Hz peak that sometimes appears, it looks about the same as 64W, except better shot noise.

,

Stability: We have had several ~day long locks, most locklosses from low noise being due to earthquakes. However, the power up from 45W to final power has been slowed down and still exhibits instabilities which cause us to lose lock. This is a terrible place to lose lock, because it takes 30min to get to this point so it's a big duty cycle impact. This problem is not new, it's been happening all of O4b, it's just more now that we do more steps. A ~2.7 Hz oscillation appears and runs away, seemingly largest in DARM, which is confusing. We remeasured the cross-over of L1/L2 which has an instability near there, but it has 6dB of margin and it makes no sense it would be power dependent.

However, we realized that during power up steps we turn off the SRM angular loop (SRC2), and as the power up step got longer and longer, maybe it's not ok to have the SRM not follow the alignment shifts in power up. The loop is slow so it would overcorrect for quick power steps, but since we've slowed them down over time, Adam added into guardian to turn this loop on in between the power steps (still have to assess the time constant it needs and optimize). After failing to power up 5 times in a row without it, with this modification it worked, but we'll wait for more statistics to see the true color of the herring.

]","{'term': 'L1 ISC', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

101,L1 ISC - Y-TR_A whitening disabled,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=72553,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Wed, 07 Aug 2024 11:12:44 -0500","[

Following up on yesterday's re-cabling [72519], initial look through the TR_A signals showed nothing.

Quadrants 1,2,4 have very little power on them; whilst almost all of the light falls on quadrant 3.

,

Upon disabling the ISC Whitening (which I can do on TR_A as opposed to TR_B, because it's a spare sensor) I think I can see something that might potentially be the signal in quadrants 1,2,4 (but not 3). Whitening gain still 3dB, which gets set in the ISC_LOCK, but that gain is fine.

This was done by turning off the Whitening as well as the Anti-whitening in the Y-TR_A screen, which don't appear to be set by guardians.

,

I have set up a number of readouts in the PI Y-arm readout system to record the frequency range 10-11kHz into a few DQ channels, with a few different QPD readout arrangements to see which combination gives the best signal (if the signal is indeed real).

I will wait on a lockloss and examine whether what I see moves as expected through thermalisation, or if it is just static noise.

,

I have stored the ISC Whitening SDF changes in both the observe.snap as well as the safe.snap in-case it reloads the safe in some situation.

]","{'term': 'L1 ISC', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: vladimir.bossilkov@ligo.org

Report ID: 72553

Following up on yesterday's re-cabling [72519], initial look through the TR_A signals showed nothing.
Quadrants 1,2,4 have very little power on them; whilst almost all of the light falls on quadrant 3.

Upon disabling the ISC Whitening (which I can do on TR_A as opposed to TR_B, because it's a spare sensor) I think I can see something that might potentially be the signal in quadrants 1,2,4 (but not 3). Whitening gain still 3dB, which gets set in the ISC_LOCK, but that gain is fine.
This was done by turning off the Whitening as well as the Anti-whitening in the Y-TR_A screen, which don't appear to be set by guardians.

I have set up a number of readouts in the PI Y-arm readout system to record the frequency range 10-11kHz into a few DQ channels, with a few different QPD readout arrangements to see which combination gives the best signal (if the signal is indeed real).
I will wait on a lockloss and examine whether what I see moves as expected through thermalisation, or if it is just static noise.

I have stored the ISC Whitening SDF changes in both the observe.snap as well as the safe.snap in-case it reloads the safe in some situation.

"

Author: robert.cottingham@ligo.org

Report ID: 72550

August 7th

9:40 AM -  Local Y-arm ion pump, 7000V & 29 uA.  Pressure in the RGA volume is 5.4E(-7) Torr.  The drop in pressure from the high 2.0E(-6) Torr at 4:15 PM yesterday indicates we're cooking off residual gas on the gatevalve face.

Cooler morning room temp 23.3C/74F at Y-Mid.  RGA heat controllers fluctuate from 195C to 201C.  The gatevalve's heat controller fluctuates from 118C to 121C.  Checked for uniform temps with K-type thermocouple and meter.  Everything looks good.
RGA is going to soak at setpoint for 1-3 weeks, we will have to monitor pressures and see how long the bake takes.

104,"LLO VE - Y-mid RGA bakeout, WP 11532.",https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=72548,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Wed, 07 Aug 2024 09:14:40 -0500","[

Bob C.

,

WP 11532.

,

We previously have been unsucessful at getting the Y-mid RGA gas load of H2O at 18 m/z, CO & N2 load at 28 m/z, CO2 at 44 m/z, and other peaks 49-57, 69, 76-77, and 90-91 m/z low enough to make the RGA common with the arm.  While the pressure in the Y-mid RGA manifold is lower than the Y-arm, a lot of the gas in the Y-arm is hydrogen and the RGA gas load is dominated by water.

,

Switching up our approach, it appears the face of the sealing plate on the CF8"" gatevalve seperating the Y-mid RGA from the Y-arm is acting as a cold spot in the 200C RGA bakeout.  I wrapped the entire gatevalve in heat tape and started a 6-hour ramp up from 25C --> 120C.  Gatevalve reached its soak temperature around 4:15 PM yesterday of 120C/248F, rated bake temperature in the closed position is 150C/302F.  The middle of the gate and both CF8"" flanges are wrapped in low wattage per linear ft heat tape for even heating.  Plotted is the local gauges on the Y-arm.The back of the gatevalve is common with the arm, so we were monitoring the pressures during the bakeout.  Pressures peaked and are returning to normal while the GV is hot.

,

August 6th.

,

8:45 AM - Started wrapping the CF8"" GV with heat tape.  Tested ramp up and the 4 ft heat tape was insufficent at even heating.  Switched to 8 ft heat tape with the same current draw as the 4 ft to get more even temperatures.  Pressure in the RGA volume was 7E(-10) Torr with the RGA fillament hot but turned off immediatly before logging pressure.

,

10:30 AM - Finished wrapping the small gatevalve in insulation with the second configuration.  Slowly started warming up the 8"" gatevalve to verify even heating.

,

11:00 AM - Heating nice and even.  Ramped up CF*"" GV to 120C and the rest of the RGA manifold to 150C before heading to lunch.  Watched the rampup for about 20 minutes to verify there's no hot or cold spots.  Pressure in the RGA manifold increased to 1.2E(-8) Torr.

,

1:50 PM - Checked pressure and heating again at the Y-mid RGA.  Bumped the RGA manifold up to 200C and checking the gatevalve, its at 104C.  RGA manifold pressure 7.7E(-7) Torr once the temperature hit 200C,

,

4:15 PM - Gatevalve at 119C when entering the Y-mid, floating around 120C.  Presure at a nice and high 2.0E(-6) Torr, which is higher than we've seen previously in the RGA volume during bakeout.  Pressure in the local gauges in the arm at PT-753 are elevated, going from 1.8E(-9) Torr in the cool morning to right under 2E(-8) Torr in the 99F afternoon.  All the local gauges appear to have peaked and leveled off.

,

August 7th.

,

7:50 AM - Pressure at gauges PT-753, 973, and 760 peaked, with 973 and 960 lagging 753 by about 3 hours.  Pressure is on the downward trend, see attached plot.  Ion pump current roughly trends the gauges.

,

9:10 AM - Going to go to the Y-mid to check on everything again to verify we still are at our soak temperature.

]","{'term': 'LLO VE', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: robert.cottingham@ligo.org

Report ID: 72548

Bob C.

We previously have been unsucessful at getting the Y-mid RGA gas load of H2O at 18 m/z, CO & N2 load at 28 m/z, CO2 at 44 m/z, and other peaks 49-57, 69, 76-77, and 90-91 m/z low enough to make the RGA common with the arm.  While the pressure in the Y-mid RGA manifold is lower than the Y-arm, a lot of the gas in the Y-arm is hydrogen and the RGA gas load is dominated by water.

Switching up our approach, it appears the face of the sealing plate on the CF8" gatevalve seperating the Y-mid RGA from the Y-arm is acting as a cold spot in the 200C RGA bakeout.  I wrapped the entire gatevalve in heat tape and started a 6-hour ramp up from 25C --> 120C.  Gatevalve reached its soak temperature around 4:15 PM yesterday of 120C/248F, rated bake temperature in the closed position is 150C/302F.  The middle of the gate and both CF8" flanges are wrapped in low wattage per linear ft heat tape for even heating.  Plotted is the local gauges on the Y-arm.The back of the gatevalve is common with the arm, so we were monitoring the pressures during the bakeout.  Pressures peaked and are returning to normal while the GV is hot.

8:45 AM - Started wrapping the CF8" GV with heat tape.  Tested ramp up and the 4 ft heat tape was insufficent at even heating.  Switched to 8 ft heat tape with the same current draw as the 4 ft to get more even temperatures.  Pressure in the RGA volume was 7E(-10) Torr with the RGA fillament hot but turned off immediatly before logging pressure.
10:30 AM - Finished wrapping the small gatevalve in insulation with the second configuration.  Slowly started warming up the 8" gatevalve to verify even heating.

11:00 AM - Heating nice and even.  Ramped up CF*" GV to 120C and the rest of the RGA manifold to 150C before heading to lunch.  Watched the rampup for about 20 minutes to verify there's no hot or cold spots.  Pressure in the RGA manifold increased to 1.2E(-8) Torr.

1:50 PM - Checked pressure and heating again at the Y-mid RGA.  Bumped the RGA manifold up to 200C and checking the gatevalve, its at 104C.  RGA manifold pressure 7.7E(-7) Torr once the temperature hit 200C,

4:15 PM - Gatevalve at 119C when entering the Y-mid, floating around 120C.  Presure at a nice and high 2.0E(-6) Torr, which is higher than we've seen previously in the RGA volume during bakeout.  Pressure in the local gauges in the arm at PT-753 are elevated, going from 1.8E(-9) Torr in the cool morning to right under 2E(-8) Torr in the 99F afternoon.  All the local gauges appear to have peaked and leveled off.

7:50 AM - Pressure at gauges PT-753, 973, and 760 peaked, with 973 and 960 lagging 753 by about 3 hours.  Pressure is on the downward trend, see attached plot.  Ion pump current roughly trends the gauges.
9:10 AM - Going to go to the Y-mid to check on everything again to verify we still are at our soak temperature.

Report ID: 72538

Weyerhaeuser will begin working around the site, most likely, at the beginning of next week. According to the Weyerhaeuser Rep., there will be mechanical site prep to prepare the sites for planting this fall/winter.  The work will consist of shearing and plowing.  The contractor who is doing this work typically has a two man crew working with one operating a dozer making a shear pass, followed by another operator on a skidder with a plow.  He doesn’t know specific start and stop times on a daily basis, but he assumes they start pretty early and work pretty late.  He will ask the contractor foreman to inform me of their plans for start and end times.  The acreage highlighted in blue (map attached) should take about 2 ½ to 3 weeks to complete, weather permitting. He'll keep me posted on an exact start date when he finds out.

123,L1 CDS - Comment to Beckhoff slow controls windows machine crashed,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=72530,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Tue, 06 Aug 2024 11:43:27 -0500",[],"{'term': 'L1 CDS', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: joseph.betzwieser@ligo.org

Report ID: 72530

The two power supplies in the back of the l1ecatc1 machine seemed to trip off during the boot process. I had gone in, hit the power button for 3 seconds, which cycled it off, and then hit the power button. I confirmed lights were coming back on, and then walked away.

After waiting awhile and still unable to log in, I walked back to the MSR and found all lights dark on the l1ecatc1 machine.  I went to the back and found the power supply lights dark, despite the power supply switches in the on position.  I confirmed cables were still plugged in, and other machines plugged into the power strip were on.  I then flicked the two power supply rocker switches to off, and then on again. This seemed to restart the power supplies, and the power lights came on.  The computer proceeded to boot properly.
It is unclear to me why the power supplies seemed to trip off on a standard power cycle.CDS"

8,H1 PSL - PSL 9.5Hz Comb Hunt (LHO WP 12031),https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=79533,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Tue, 13 Aug 2024 12:28:53 -0700","[

J. Oberling, F. Clara

,

Summary: We think the 9.5Hz peak is coming from the new flow meters installed as part of the 2021 PSL laser upgrade.

,

Today we continued hunting for the 9.5Hz comb triplet that Ansel had tracked to the PSL back in May.  Robert subsequently used a temporary magnetometer and found a strong 9.5Hz feature in the neoLASE LVEA Control Box.  To try to isolate the source of this 9.5Hz peak we shut down the PSL in a controlled manner and watched the peak on the magnetometer.  The order of the shutdown:

,

There was no change in the peak observed during the PSL shutdown, so we next turned off the neoLASE Control Box; the peak clearly disappeared with the Control Box off.  Our next step was to check if the peak was being fed to the Control Box via something plugged into it.  We turned the Control Box back on and the peak returned (as expected), then we unplugged the cable that feeds the flow/temperature sensor signals to the Control Box (via the PSL Sensor Interface Chassis (SIC), which feeds the Control Box with several monitor signals (PDs, power meters, flow meters) and the system shutters).  Lo and behold, the peak was much smaller, sometimes disappearing entirely (see attached pictures; first is with the PSL off but the flow meters plugged in, second is with the flow meters unplugged).  We next took the top off of the SIC and placed the magnetometer near where the flow meter signals both come into and exit the SIC, and did not see the peak.  Fil then placed the magnetometer on the flow sensor connectors themselves (the flow sensor cables route to a pig tail on the back of the SIC, which goes from an individual M12 connector for each flow meter into a DB25 connector to plug into the SIC) and the 9.5Hz peak was clearly visible again. If we unplugged the main flow meter cable from the back of the Control Box the peak again disappeard; this makes sense as the Control Box supplies the 24 VDC the flow meters need, and unplugging the cable removes power from the flow meters.  We then put the top back on the SIC and placed the magnetometer back in its spot directly underneath the Control Box and plugged the flow meters back in; the peak again returned.  Fil disconnected the individual M12 connectors for the flow meters and the peak again disappeared.  We then plugged each individual flow meter in to observe how the peak behaved (I did not take pictures of this, unfortunately).  With 1 flow meter plugged in the peak was visible but much smaller; with 2 plugged in the peak was even smaller (???); with three plugged in the peak was back to its usual magnitude.  With this odd behavior we suspect a grounding issue somewhere.  To finish things off we unplugged the other items feeding signals into the Control Box (shutters, PDs/power meters, NPRO, Diode Box A, Diode Box B), one at a time, to observe how/if the peak changed; we observed no change in the peak during this process, the only thing that changed the peak with the Control Box turned on was unplugging the flow meter cable.  We think this fairly definitively tags the flow meters as the source for the 9.5Hz peak seen in Robert's magnetometer, and likely the source of the comb triplet seen around this frequency.

,

We are now looking through documentation to see how we can mitigate this.  One option is to tie the grounds of all 3 flow meters together and see if this changes the peak; this requires running long cables from each flow meter to tie them all at the same spot.  We also plan on using the spare Control Box to check into how the internal grounding of the Beckhoff terminal is done and see if there's any improvements we can make there.  Another option is to isolate power to the flow meters; currently they are powered by the Control Box, but we could power them separtely and see if that changes the peak.  Investigation continues, more to come.

,

The PSL is now back ON, and the PMC and FSS RefCav are locked; I'm letting the system warm up for a bit before locking the ISS.  This closes LHO WP 12031.

,

Edit to add: When unplugging the flow meters individually via their M12 connectors, we did try each of the 3 flow meters by themselves; the peak was the same regardless of which individual flow meter was plugged in.  Things got weird when we had 2 plugged in at the same time (the peak was smaller than with any of the individual flow meters plugged in, hence why we suspect a grounding issue somewhere), and the peak returned to its starting magnitude when all 3 were plugged in at the same time.

]","{'term': 'H1 PSL', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: jason.oberling@ligo.org

Report ID: 79533

J. Oberling, F. Clara
Summary: We think the 9.5Hz peak is coming from the new flow meters installed as part of the 2021 PSL laser upgrade.

Today we continued hunting for the 9.5Hz comb triplet that Ansel had tracked to the PSL back in May.  Robert subsequently used a temporary magnetometer and found a strong 9.5Hz feature in the neoLASE LVEA Control Box.  To try to isolate the source of this 9.5Hz peak we shut down the PSL in a controlled manner and watched the peak on the magnetometer.  The order of the shutdown:

There was no change in the peak observed during the PSL shutdown, so we next turned off the neoLASE Control Box; the peak clearly disappeared with the Control Box off.  Our next step was to check if the peak was being fed to the Control Box via something plugged into it.  We turned the Control Box back on and the peak returned (as expected), then we unplugged the cable that feeds the flow/temperature sensor signals to the Control Box (via the PSL Sensor Interface Chassis (SIC), which feeds the Control Box with several monitor signals (PDs, power meters, flow meters) and the system shutters).  Lo and behold, the peak was much smaller, sometimes disappearing entirely (see attached pictures; first is with the PSL off but the flow meters plugged in, second is with the flow meters unplugged).  We next took the top off of the SIC and placed the magnetometer near where the flow meter signals both come into and exit the SIC, and did not see the peak.  Fil then placed the magnetometer on the flow sensor connectors themselves (the flow sensor cables route to a pig tail on the back of the SIC, which goes from an individual M12 connector for each flow meter into a DB25 connector to plug into the SIC) and the 9.5Hz peak was clearly visible again. If we unplugged the main flow meter cable from the back of the Control Box the peak again disappeard; this makes sense as the Control Box supplies the 24 VDC the flow meters need, and unplugging the cable removes power from the flow meters.  We then put the top back on the SIC and placed the magnetometer back in its spot directly underneath the Control Box and plugged the flow meters back in; the peak again returned.  Fil disconnected the individual M12 connectors for the flow meters and the peak again disappeared.  We then plugged each individual flow meter in to observe how the peak behaved (I did not take pictures of this, unfortunately).  With 1 flow meter plugged in the peak was visible but much smaller; with 2 plugged in the peak was even smaller (???); with three plugged in the peak was back to its usual magnitude.  With this odd behavior we suspect a grounding issue somewhere.  To finish things off we unplugged the other items feeding signals into the Control Box (shutters, PDs/power meters, NPRO, Diode Box A, Diode Box B), one at a time, to observe how/if the peak changed; we observed no change in the peak during this process, the only thing that changed the peak with the Control Box turned on was unplugging the flow meter cable.  We think this fairly definitively tags the flow meters as the source for the 9.5Hz peak seen in Robert's magnetometer, and likely the source of the comb triplet seen around this frequency.

We are now looking through documentation to see how we can mitigate this.  One option is to tie the grounds of all 3 flow meters together and see if this changes the peak; this requires running long cables from each flow meter to tie them all at the same spot.  We also plan on using the spare Control Box to check into how the internal grounding of the Beckhoff terminal is done and see if there's any improvements we can make there.  Another option is to isolate power to the flow meters; currently they are powered by the Control Box, but we could power them separtely and see if that changes the peak.  Investigation continues, more to come.
The PSL is now back ON, and the PMC and FSS RefCav are locked; I'm letting the system warm up for a bit before locking the ISS.  This closes LHO WP 12031.

Edit to add: When unplugging the flow meters individually via their M12 connectors, we did try each of the 3 flow meters by themselves; the peak was the same regardless of which individual flow meter was plugged in.  Things got weird when we had 2 plugged in at the same time (the peak was smaller than with any of the individual flow meters plugged in, hence why we suspect a grounding issue somewhere), and the peak returned to its starting magnitude when all 3 were plugged in at the same time.

14,H1 CAL - h1calcs model updated to divide by zero issue in coherence block,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=79527,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Mon, 12 Aug 2024 19:08:43 -0700",[],"{'term': 'H1 CAL', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: louis.dartez@ligo.org

Report ID: 79527

This is a sister alog to LLO:72613. After discussion with the calibration group, Joe and I have proposed and pushed a small but important fix to the CAL_LINE_MONITOR_MASTER/COHERENCE block. When the IFOs are down, the coherence for various calibration and monitoring line transfer functions is 0 (this is good). However, the TF uncertainty, which is also produced by the coherence block, was found to be railing at 0 too. How can the uncertainty be 0 if there is no coherence?! It turns out that a coherence of 0 was causing a divide by 0 that, on the front end, presents as ... you guessed it, 0. The new h1calcs models (updated at LLO then synchronized by me to LHO) fix that.

Now the coherence signal entering the uncertainty-calculation logic will be kept within 1e-6 to 2. We allowed for a coh value above 2 in order to avoid inadvertently 'hiding' egregious errors in the coherence calculation by forcing it to stay below 1. Thinking about this further now that I'm writing this...that wasn't necessary as the coherence channel itself isn't affected by our new changes. oh well.
I've attached an annotated screenshot of Joe's screenshot in LLO:72613 to show the new component we've installed.
The h1calcs updates should be put in place during tomorrow's maintenance period.AOS

15,LHO VE - 8-12 vent vacuum diary,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=79526,https://alog.ligo-wa.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Mon, 12 Aug 2024 17:54:40 -0700",[],"{'term': 'LHO VE', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: janos.csizmazia@ligo.org

Report ID: 79526

Today's activities:
- After reaching ~1.6E-6 Torr in the Corner (according to BSC3's gauge), GV1 was opened. This immediately brought down the corner pressure to ~9E-7 Torr
- A few hours after this, GV2 was also opened. This quickly brought down the pressure further to ~6.5E-7 Torr

- Opening up of GV1 and GV2 was 2 steps of a strategy, which used the Y and X manifolds as ""vacuum accumulators"" (the turbo pumps were switched on these volumes for the entire vent, so the pressure in these volumes was very low - ~2-3E-8 Torr). This came with immediate pressure drops, and now there is 6500 l/s pumping speed in the corner instead of the 2500 l/s. This means now a ~15 m^3/h real throughput instead of ~1.5 m^3/h before these actions

- Because of these openings, the pressure in CP2 started to rise slowly, because GV7 was only soft-closed. So, after reaching 3.4E-9 Torr, more pressure was applied to GV7 - it was noticed, that most likely because of the inst. air actions, the pressure there was very low, <5 psi. Now it was set to ~12 psi, and so CP2 pressure stabilized

26,L1 SUS - PUM coil driver change need better compensation for calibration,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=72645,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Tue, 13 Aug 2024 17:51:35 -0500",[],"{'term': 'L1 SUS', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: joseph.betzwieser@ligo.org

Report ID: 72645

[Vlad B, Louis D, Joe B]

Louis reminded me that the new PUM driver installed in ETMX (see LLO alog 72635) needed its digital compensation updated. We took a sweep, and realized the frequency dependent change looked to be around 4% at the worst points (see second attachment). We worried this was going to negatively effect the calibration significantly, and so were trying to apply a corrected compensation filter based on old measurements of the S1200470 (see LLO alog 58800 but apparently repairs on the readback side of things affected the transfer function of the coildriver itself significantly. The third attachment has what would have been corrected if we used the old S1200470 fit to correct the current compensation, which doesn't match up to the calibration PUM sweep.

According to our many PCAL monitoring lines, the response looks within 2% up to 1 kHz. See for example here. Louis also took a broadband between 20 and 200 Hz, and compared it to the one taken on Saturday, and while there is a perceptible difference, it also seems on the order of 2%.

I'll need to take several hours of measurements of the coil driver in situ for its various states to get the current response of the coil driver, and then update the digital compensation.  However, for now the calibration looks to be in an acceptable state, so it can wait until Tuesday if necessary.CAL, SUS

53,L1 CAL - Commissioning PHYSICAL TDEP path to produce optical gain in mA/m,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=72617,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Mon, 12 Aug 2024 20:58:40 -0500",[],"{'term': 'L1 CAL', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: louis.dartez@ligo.org

Report ID: 72617

I've populated the necessary channels to produce the L1 optical gain in physical units (mA/m) on the front end.*

There is new logic in CAL-CS to convert kappaC to mA/m. To find this in MEDM go to sitemap->CAL->CAL-CS_DARM->CAL LINE MONITORS, DEMODS & TIME DEPENDENT PARAMETER CALCULATIONS (purple block on left)->T1700106 EQ 15 (green vertical block towards right).
The conversion from kappaC to true optical gain (mA/m) is:
kappaC (dimensionless) * Hc at calibration export (DARM_ERR cnt/m) * L1:OMC-DCPD_SUM_OUT/L1:LSC-DARM_IN1 (mA/DARM_ERR cnts)

We take Hc in (DARM_ERR cnt/m) from the last exported calibration report. At the time of this writing this is 20240408T200652Z. The number is taken from the table printed on the bottom of the first page of this report.

The last term in (mA/DARM_ERR cnts) can either be measured in diaggui or calculated deterministically by inspecting the path from OMC-DCPD_SUM_OUT to LSC-DARM_IN1. By doing the latter, I've calculated the TF factor from OMC-DCPD_SUM_OUT to LSC-DARM_IN1 to be -16.8632 (mA/DARM_ERR cnts). Taking the absolute value and multiplying the result by the optical gain (in DARM_ERR cnt/m) reported in the last exported calibration report gives 9.7739e12 (mA/cnt). Placing this number in L1:CAL-CS_TDEP_OPT_GAIN_MA_PER_CNT produces the corrected optical gain in L1:CAL-CS_TDEP_OPT_GAIN_PHYSICAL in units of mA/m. I also populated L1:CAL-CS_TDEP_OPT_GAIN_NORM_REFERENCE with the same value so that L1:CAL-CS_TDEP_OPT_GAIN_NORMALIZED shows the current optical gain normalized by the optical gain when the last calibration update took place. Now commissioners can use L1:CAL-CS_TDEP_OPT_GAIN_NORM_REFERENCE to compare the current optical gain against the optical gain at some prior point in time as a fractional value.
Here are the commands I used to set the TDEP channels to produce the optical gain in units of mA/m:

* I've ""cheated"" here in the sense that the EPICS values I updated were installed by hand. In the future pyDARM will take care of this automatically every time a new calibration report is 'exported' to the front end. I've done this because 1.) the pyDARM changes aren't yet in place and 2.) this has already been shown to be needed/useful for ongoing commissioning efforts here at LLOAOS

60,"L1 SQZ - Comment to Low range, sqz on off test: It's not the squeezer",https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=72609,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Mon, 12 Aug 2024 12:36:40 -0500",[],"{'term': 'L1 SQZ', 'scheme': None, 'label': None}","

Author: joseph.betzwieser@ligo.org

Report ID: 72609

I was looking at temperatures in the building (since I was confused by the Jan 5 1980 timestamp that Mike had for his LVEA temp in the above temperature plot), and then also at our vertical OSEM readouts for the ETMs, and then BS as well since the general LVEA temperature didn't seem to be as well regulated the last 2 weeks. The vertical OSEMs drifts don't line up with the variations, although the ETMX and BS do seem to have drifted ever so slightly downward over the last few weeks, so I could maybe say we're we're sampling a different position parameter space, but seems unlikely to me.
L0:FMC-EX_VEA_AVTEMP channel hasn't changed since Jan 30th, and before that was also constant for months, so probably needs to be fixed.  I've put an FRS in for it.

Certainly the variations feel like a temperature cadence, although time shifted from any of our actual temperature sensors.  The PEM-EX_TEMPERATURE_BSC4_ETMX_MON seems to at least peak around the time of our lowest range, but even just a few weeks ago we had higher measured temperatures from that sensor, so it seems unlikely.

Also, in interests of looking at relative drifts and/or in chamber thermometers, I looked at the reaction chain OSEM signals, both R0 and also the L2 stage OSEMs.  Nothing really correlated or that obviously different than 4 or 5 days ago.  There's some longer term drifts, but I feel like we should have been suffering this noise earlier if they were connected.

Author: adam.mullavey@ligo.org

Report ID: 72608

Common Mode Loop Gain

I remeasured the open loop gain of the Common Mode loop, see attached. The gain is a little lower than we usually keep it, currently the UGF is ~7kHz and in the past we've kept it between 10 and 20kHz. The last time I measured it was in February 2023, this was when the final IFO power was set to 50W. On that occassion I had set it up so that the UGF would be 15kHz. We should look at increasing this gain, but before we do that, I'd like to remeasure the FSS and IMC gains, as the CM loop is nested on top of these loops.

In addition to the initial code changes made for 71W (see alog 72464), I've now set the POWER_UP_FINAL state in the ISC_LOCK guardian to turn the ASC SRC2 loops back on after each power up step, i.e. after powering up to 56.7W, 63.7W and 71.5W. The loop stays on until the next power up step, which is set by how long it takes for the BS and ETM camera spots to re-centered within they're thresholds. We may want to consider putting in some code that waits for the POPAIR-90I to re-settle below some value.

Author: joseph.betzwieser@ligo.org

Report ID: 72607

As far as calibration is concerned, kappa_C calculation is correct. We have been seeing changes in the effective SRC detuning at low frequencies, but the overall impact on the calibration is limited to a +/-2% wiggle in the lower half of the spectrum. See for example the attached calibration sweep from this weekend. First plot is showing the difference between the latest sweep fit parameters and the currently exported model. Since actuation has a larger effect on the overall calibration than sensing at low frequencies (i.e. below the DARM UGF of around 65 Hz), this effect on the overall calibration is reduced.
This changing SRC detuning may have been impacting the correct squeezer settings.
Once we've settled on a final power and TCS settings, we need to push a new calibration derived from a set of sweeps during that final configuration to tighten up the overall calibration.CAL

72,L1 SQZ - Comment to Brief summary of 71W power-up commissioning,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=72594,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Sun, 11 Aug 2024 14:55:51 -0500","[

Some notes on the squeezer and TCS changes: 

,

With the 71W configuration, with TCS changes, I've been making adjustments to bring the squeezing level to ~ -5.3 dB levels using the squeezer phase. This change mostly accounts for the path length change due to the thermo-refractive changes experienced by the test masses, i.e. wavefront distortion within the substrates. To correct for the quadratic mode-mismatch between the IFO beam and the squeezed beam, due to the thermo-elastic surface deformation effect, we will need to sweep the ZM4 and ZM5 PSAMS, i.e. the defocus on the squeezed beam.

As important as the wavefront curvature, misalignment of a beam also imprints an effective tilt on the wavefront, compromising the mode-matching, i.e. the electric field overlap. So, to recover our optimal squeezing level of ~ -5.8 dB with the new TCS settings, we will need to perform fine alignment scans as well as the PSAM scans.

,

For context: Fast alignment with the SQZ guardian was attempted and yielded no improvement for the 71 W case. We have seen the need for the fine alignment and PSAM scans in keeping the squeezing level up for various thermal states: the recovery of -5.7 dB squeezing with 63.5 W alogs 72160 72287, the drop to 56 W alog 72249, partial recovery work after going back up to 63.5 W alog 72441.

,

Shot noise comparison with comparable squeezing levels: 

,

Attached is a DARM plot showing representative strains for the three different power levels, with comparable squeezing level at ~ -5.4 dB. Author: begum.kabagoz@ligo.org

Report ID: 72594

Some notes on the squeezer and TCS changes:

With the 71W configuration, with TCS changes, I've been making adjustments to bring the squeezing level to ~ -5.3 dB levels using the squeezer phase. This change mostly accounts for the path length change due to the thermo-refractive changes experienced by the test masses, i.e. wavefront distortion within the substrates. To correct for the quadratic mode-mismatch between the IFO beam and the squeezed beam, due to the thermo-elastic surface deformation effect, we will need to sweep the ZM4 and ZM5 PSAMS, i.e. the defocus on the squeezed beam.

As important as the wavefront curvature, misalignment of a beam also imprints an effective tilt on the wavefront, compromising the mode-matching, i.e. the electric field overlap. So, to recover our optimal squeezing level of ~ -5.8 dB with the new TCS settings, we will need to perform fine alignment scans as well as the PSAM scans.

For context: Fast alignment with the SQZ guardian was attempted and yielded no improvement for the 71 W case. We have seen the need for the fine alignment and PSAM scans in keeping the squeezing level up for various thermal states: the recovery of -5.7 dB squeezing with 63.5 W alogs 72160 72287, the drop to 56 W alog 72249, partial recovery work after going back up to 63.5 W alog 72441.
Shot noise comparison with comparable squeezing levels:

Attached is a DARM plot showing representative strains for the three different power levels, with comparable squeezing level at ~ -5.4 dB. The black trace is taken with 71 W, the purple trace is with 63.5 W, and the green trace is with 56.7 W input power. The high frequency noise around 4-7 kHz is also comparable for the 63.5 W and 71 W cases. Low frequency noise looks about the same for all three power levels in this plot, with the improvement in shot noise with increasing power visible >300 Hz.

These strains were chosen from times where we are not hindered by the low frequnecy nonstationary noise that shows up sporadically. The measurements are taken over a 10 minute period in each case. The dtt location: /data/begum.kabagoz/TCS_and_SQZ/gds_calib_strain_comparison.xml

,

Seems our fix from yesterday didn't fix everything. A few notes, since we still don't understand the mechanism:
- we measured ASC MICH P and Y, they are fine;
- we measured the OMC OLG, it's at 10 Hz instead of 20 Hz but still enough phase margin (we'll consult Adam Monday if to raise the gain for good);
- we tried slightly increasing the SRC2 gains, from 1 to 1.2, that didn't help;
- we decreased the CHARD P gain from 0.3 to 0.2 during the power up, and put it back later, but unclear if this helped (there's no instability in CHARD at 2.7 but there may be one around 2 Hz);

- OMC yaw signals see it at perhaps worrisome level, and larger there first than in DARM.

,

The SRC2 loop only gets turned on every other power step, strangely, and doesn't fully converge by the time it's turned off to do another step. The two times we lost lock in the final power up stage due to 2.7 Hz instability today, it was some 1min - 30 sec or so after it had been re-engaged.

- OMC yaw signals see it at perhaps worrisome level, and larger there first than in DARM.

The SRC2 loop only gets turned on every other power step, strangely, and doesn't fully converge by the time it's turned off to do another step. The two times we lost lock in the final power up stage due to 2.7 Hz instability today, it was some 1min - 30 sec or so after it had been re-engaged.

99,L1 ISC - Brief summary of 71W power-up commissioning,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/index.php?callRep=72568,https://alog.ligo-la.caltech.edu/aLOG/rss-feed.php,"Fri, 09 Aug 2024 12:43:33 -0500","[

Valera, Adam, Begum, Karla, Vlad, JoeB, Anamaria

,

For the past some 10 days we've been running at ~71W input power, above the nominal ~64W. I will try to summarize some of our activities and findings so far.

,

In the first 3 plots I show the same top two panels and time span, and then different signals related to different observations (so they're more visible than if I were to plot 10 panels). The top plot is the input power over the past 20 days. We had to operate at even lower power (56W) for a bit because the CO2 alignment had been lost, so it's interesting to compare the 3 input power behaviors. The second plot is kappa_c, the indicator of optical gain; it should not change with power the way it is calculated. We always lose a bit of optical gain as we go up in power, but it's superficially still worth it if we lose less than we gain in shot noise level. 

,

In the first plot attached, the third signal is the POP power, calibrated in W in the PRC. Based on Valera's estimate of arm power, we think this corresponds to ~280kW/307kW/335kW circulating in the arm for the 3 power settings. The next signal is the 9 mHz buildup in the PRC, scaled by input power. It seems to go down no matter what. For reference, the current ~1700 value corresponds to a buildup of 70, while the perfect mode matching estimate is ~120. The 45 MHz buildup is much smaller by design, ~13 in a perfect world, and it does something similar to the 9MHz so I don't show it here.

,

This 9 MHz buildup drop has us concerned about the stability of various loops, since it's the identical behavior that LHO saw during their highest power operations. We measured the PRCL loop as a good indicator of this, but it seems to so far not lose too much gain. Adam also measured the CARM loop yesterday, and it seemed a bit not ideal, he will post details separately, but more measurements are necessary and we will do them in the next commissioning period. 

,

In the second plot attached, I show also range (after calibration) with optical gain and squeezer performance, since both affect range significantly. With every power adjustment and large TCS changes, the squeezer has to be readjusted, which Begum has been doing this entire period. During all these changes, albeit small in the grand scheme of things, the range seems slightly  lower for the higher power, but that's to be expected for the optimization period. We've definitely found a better thermal state in the past few days and we hope to get some more data to have a more fair comparison with the nominal 64W operation.

,

In the third plot attached, I show some of the TCS setting changes. At 56W we can afford to run without CO2, which is a good state to have automated in case of hardware issues. We then tried two different settings at 71W, ~2.0W and ~2.4W. We were hoping we can trade CO2 for ITM ring heater to increase the sideband buildup without losing optical gain (because they have different lensing versus curvature effect). So far we can't say we found this to be true or quantified it, but we will continue. With the higher CO2 setting we were indeed able to reduce the ITM RH power below the 64W settings to increase the optical gain. We have not tested much ETM ring heater effects yet, still to check.
We are also trying to decipher if the Hartmann signals and the SIM signals could be useful for tuning, we will separately make a report on that.

Vlad will post an optical mode shift report in various configurations, to see if we can use it for carrier mode matching improvement.

,

Thermal transient: it does seem to be much longer as we increase the nominal low noise CO2 values. We are trying to understand it to see if we can speed it up. Right now we apply about half of it right after DC readout, and the rest after we've powered up, but there's no matching done with the central transient. This alone could be an argument for running at lower power, since we lose range in the first few hours of the lock, especially because of the squeezer transient that has elongated as well.

The differential element also has a long trasient (not shown), long locks start with higher frequency coupling, which then goes down over a few hours and settles at a reasonable value. This can be seen directly in DARM at ~5-6kHz where the frequency noise is close: when that region has a bump, we have more coupling/contrast defect/differential lensing.

,

Noise:  We don't have a deep assessment yet of the noise comparison, there may be a bit of low frequency noise at the higher power, but that's confounded with squeezer operation. We will post a noise curve later. Aside from a ~20 Hz peak that sometimes appears, it looks about the same as 64W, except better shot noise.

,

Stability: We have had several ~day long locks, most locklosses from low noise being due to earthquakes. However, the power up from 45W to final power has been slowed down and still exhibits instabilities which cause us to lose lock. This is a terrible place to lose lock, because it takes 30min to get to this point so it's a big duty cycle impact. This problem is not new, it's been happening all of O4b, it's just more now that we do more steps. A ~2.7 Hz oscillation appears and runs away, seemingly largest in DARM, which is confusing. We remeasured the cross-over of L1/L2 which has an instability near there, but it has 6dB of margin and it makes no sense it would be power dependent.

However, we realized that during power up steps we turn off the SRM angular loop (SRC2), and as the power up step got longer and longer, maybe it's not ok to have the SRM not follow the alignment shifts in power up. The loop is slow so it would overcorrect for quick power steps, but since we've slowed them down over time, Adam added into guardian to turn this loop on in between the power steps (still have to assess the time constant it needs and optimize). After failing to power up 5 times in a row without it, with this modification it worked, but we'll wait for more statistics to see the true color of the herring.

For the past some 10 days we've been running at ~71W input power, above the nominal ~64W. I will try to summarize some of our activities and findings so far.

In the first 3 plots I show the same top two panels and time span, and then different signals related to different observations (so they're more visible than if I were to plot 10 panels). The top plot is the input power over the past 20 days. We had to operate at even lower power (56W) for a bit because the CO2 alignment had been lost, so it's interesting to compare the 3 input power behaviors. The second plot is kappa_c, the indicator of optical gain; it should not change with power the way it is calculated. We always lose a bit of optical gain as we go up in power, but it's superficially still worth it if we lose less than we gain in shot noise level.

In the first plot attached, the third signal is the POP power, calibrated in W in the PRC. Based on Valera's estimate of arm power, we think this corresponds to ~280kW/307kW/335kW circulating in the arm for the 3 power settings. The next signal is the 9 mHz buildup in the PRC, scaled by input power. It seems to go down no matter what. For reference, the current ~1700 value corresponds to a buildup of 70, while the perfect mode matching estimate is ~120. The 45 MHz buildup is much smaller by design, ~13 in a perfect world, and it does something similar to the 9MHz so I don't show it here.

This 9 MHz buildup drop has us concerned about the stability of various loops, since it's the identical behavior that LHO saw during their highest power operations. We measured the PRCL loop as a good indicator of this, but it seems to so far not lose too much gain. Adam also measured the CARM loop yesterday, and it seemed a bit not ideal, he will post details separately, but more measurements are necessary and we will do them in the next commissioning period.

In the second plot attached, I show also range (after calibration) with optical gain and squeezer performance, since both affect range significantly. With every power adjustment and large TCS changes, the squeezer has to be readjusted, which Begum has been doing this entire period. We are also trying to decipher if the Hartmann signals and the SIM signals could be useful for tuning, we will separately make a report on that.
Vlad will post an optical mode shift report in various configurations, to see if we can use it for carrier mode matching improvement.

Thermal transient: it does seem to be much longer as we increase the nominal low noise CO2 values. We are trying to understand it to see if we can speed it up. Right now we apply about half of it right after DC readout, and the rest after we've powered up, but there's no matching done with the central transient. This alone could be an argument for running at lower power, since we lose range in the first few hours of the lock, especially because of the squeezer transient that has elongated as well.

The differential element also has a long trasient (not shown), long locks start with higher frequency coupling, which then goes down over a few hours and settles at a reasonable value. This can be seen directly in DARM at ~5-6kHz where the frequency noise is close: when that region has a bump, we have more coupling/contrast defect/differential lensing.

Noise:  We don't have a deep assessment yet of the noise comparison, there may be a bit of low frequency noise at the higher power, but that's confounded with squeezer operation.
